info.name: DoseSpot Postman Collections Jumpstart
info.description:
# Introduction
Our Integration Plus REST API allows you to put the functions of DoseSpot into your user interface.

# Overview

# Authentication
In order to use the API, you must get a token and use it on further requests until its expiration date (about 10 minutes)

You will need to use the /token function before calling your first function and check to see if it has expired before calling additional functions.

# Real Time Formulary / Prescription Benefits API Overview

## Endpoints Involved

```
api/patients/{patientId}/therapeuticAlternatives
api/patients/{patientId}/formulary
api/patients/{patientId}/prescriptionbenefits
```

## API Modes  
* ### Realtime Formulary Disabled

    The call is blocking and the results will be in the response. This makes the APIs backwards compatible as
 the results will be the same. The *RealTimeFormularyRequestStatus* will always be FeatureDisabled (0)

* ### Realtime Formulary Enabled

    The call is non-blocking (async) so the caller will need to poll this endpoint for status updates until
the result is available or an error has occured.
\
 
## Request Status
\
 
The behavior of the APIs is dictated by the Real Time Formulary feature that is set at the client level.
When the APIs are in async mode, the caller will need to poll this endpoint and pay 
close attention to the status updates *RealTimeFormularyRequestStatus* / *ResultDescription*.

| Status                        | RealTimeFormularyRequestStatus | Description     |
| :---                          |    :----:                      |            ---: |
| FeatureDisabled               | 0                              | Real Time Formulary Mode is disabled |
| Queued                        | 1                              | Message added to DoseSpot queue |
| Sent                          | 2                              | Message Sent to SS |
| Success                       | 3                              | Request has Completed and result is available in this response |
| UnexpectedError               | 1000                           | The request failure was unexpected |
| PatientEligibilityNotFound    | 1001                           | Patient Eligibility does not exist for the given ID |
| FailedToGetAlternatives       | 1002                           | Failed to Gather Alternatives |
| PatientFormularyNotFound      | 1003                           | Patient Formulary does not exist for the given ID |
| FailedToParseFormularyData    | 1004                           | Failed to parse the response data from SureScripts |
| FailedToProcessSend           | 1005                           | After sending the message to SureScripts, a failure occurred updating this status |
| FailedToQueueMessage          | 1006                           | There was a failure queuing the message to SureScripts |
| DataExpired                   | 1007                           | The cached response data from a previous call is no longer valid (Current Expiration is 24 hours) |
| RequestExpired                | 1008                           | The request to SureScripts timed out (if the request takes longer than 5 minutes, we "cancel" it) |
| SSRespondedWithErrorCode      | 1009                           | SureScripts returned an error, the error code will be avail in *ResultDescription* |
| MissingPatientBenefitsInputs  | 1010                           | The input validation check failed for the Prescription Benefits API call |
| UnknownSSResponseSchema       | 1011                           | The expected SureScripts response schema is no longer correct |
| SSRespondedWithTxnErrorCode   | 1012                           | SureScripts responded with a transaction error code |

\
 
## API Status Update Example

```
{
    <API SPECIFIC DATA>,
    "RealTimeFormularyRequestStatus": 1,
    "Result": {
        "ResultCode": "OK",
        "ResultDescription": "realtime: message queued"
    }
}
```
## Error Handling

When an error does occur, the *RealTimeFormularyRequestStatus* / *ResultDescription* will reflect this and
the next subsequent request will trigger a new async request cycle and the client can proceed with polling.

```
{
    <API SPECIFIC DATA>,
    "RealTimeFormularyRequestStatus": 1001,
    "Result": {
        "ResultCode": "ERROR",
        "ResultDescription": "No active eligibility exists."
    }
}
```
